TY  - JOUR
AU  - Chaderina, Maria
AU  - Green, Richard C.
T1  - Predators and Prey on Wall Street
PY  - 2014
Y1  - 2014/06/01
DO  - 10.1093/rapstu/rau003
JO  - The Review of Asset Pricing Studies
JA  - Rev Asset Pric Stud
VL  - 4
IS  - 1
SP  - 1
EP  - 38
SN  - 2045-9920
AB  - Much financial activity is zero-sum. While providing transactional and diversification services to others, participants also prey upon each other. High-ability predators trade opportunistically with less-able prey. In our dynamic model these features amplify real shocks. The presence of more low-ability traders reduces expected losses to high-ability traders, leading to equilibria with high levels of financial activity and employment. Shocks to profits can motivate exit by low-ability traders, rendering those of intermediate skill more vulnerable. Thus, our relatively simple model generates boom-bust dynamics suggestive of Wall Street. (JEL G00, G20, E44)
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rapstu/rau003
ER  - 



